econdary osteoarthritis may result","Pain is usually anterior","The joint is rarely involved in shoulder injuries","It primarily affects the glenohumeral joint","It is not affected by repetitive overhead activities"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETrauma to the acromioclavicular joint can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary osteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E due to the stress and wear on the joint over time. This joint is frequently involved in shoulder injuries, especially in those who engage in repetitive overhead activities. Pain from acromioclavicular joint injury is located at the top of the shoulder, not anteriorly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The acromioclavicular joint is a common site for osteoarthritis due to its frequent use and stress.","Trauma to the acromioclavicular joint can lead to secondary osteoarthritis over time.","Pain from acromioclavicular joint injury is commonly located at the top of the shoulder, not anteriorly."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Kiel J, Taqi M, Kaiser K. Acromioclavicular Joint Injury. 2022 Sep 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29630240.","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: Gener